title: For Sale/Trade:  Heckler & Koch VP70 Z
postcontent:
What I have for sale is a Heckler & Koch VP70 Z.  This HK is a 9 mm, 18-round, double action only, semi-automatic polymer frame pistol manufactured by German arms firm Heckler & Koch GmbH. VP stands for Vollautomatische Pistole, and the designation 70 was for the year of the first edition: 1970.

The HK VP70 Z was the first polymer-framed pistol and predates the Glock 17 by 12 years. This weapon weighs 28.9 oz unloaded, lighter than most other metal framed pistols of its time.  Although it was the first polymer pistol, the Remington Nylon 66 rifle introduced in 1959 was the first polymer-framed firearm in production.

The VP70 uses a spring-loaded striker like a Glock, instead of a conventional firing pin. It is double action only so the trigger pull is relatively heavy. In lieu of a blade front sight, the VP70 uses a polished ramp with a central notch in the middle to provide the illusion of a dark front post. Contrary to a common misconception, the VP70 does indeed have a manual safety. It is the circular button located immediately behind the trigger and is a common cross block safety.

I have attached a picture of page 157 of the Modern Gun Values, 15th Edition that shows in perfect condition the gun's value is $750.00.  In my opinion, the gun is in perfect condition; however, I also realize that only a true HK collector would pay that.  

I have the original box, test target and manual.

Comes with the original 2 magazines.

title: For Sale:  Full Size CZ 75 9mm - SPF
postcontent:
SOLD PENDING FUNDS

Imported CZ 75 full size with 1 16-round MecGar magazine. Military/Police trade in. 

Not much needed to be said. This is definitely the most accurate 9mm I've shot and is an awesome and one of the best 9mms ever made. 

I have shot about 100 rounds through this and it has had no issues at all. Range buddies were very impressed with the accuracy, but those that know CZ 75s already knew this.

This is not a Pre-B model, it is actually a transitional model (1994) between the Pre-B and CZ 75B. It DOES accept MecGar mags, so that is a bonus, because Pre-B mags are hard to find and at least $40/ea. MidwayUSA sells the 16-round MecGar mags for $23, though you may find them lesser somewhere else.

This is essentially the same as a CZ 75B, which has a manual saftey and can be carried "cocked & locked", like a 1911, but no decocker.

Frame is in very good condition, but has some minor wear and some minor nicks. I doubt you will notice at all. The only noticeable wear is on the back right of the slide, but has no impact on functionality. Again, not very noticeable. Of course, the slide can be cerakoted or refinished if desired. See if you can notice on the last pic.

Barrel is in pristine condition. Firearm is cleaned well and oiled. 

CZ 75s are rare on the used market because people like to keep them. I would like to as well, but need to keep my carry piece and sell off my other 9s to pay some bills, so cannot accept any trades at this time.

The great thing about the CZ 75 is the affordability of its components if you wanted to change things out. Factory rear sight is only $9 at cz-usa.com. Front sights are only $5. Unless you want to go night sights, of course.

Priced to move. Tangfolios (CZ clones) aren't even priced this low.

Details:
-Cash only
-CPL or purchase permit required (of course)
-FTF only in public place
-will drive reasonable distance
-reply with name & phone and I'll do the same

title: For Sale:  CZ 2075 RAMI 9mm sub-compact double stack magazine
postcontent:
This 9mm sub compact is a perfect size for concealed carry and it comes with a hard polymer holster, a speed loader, one 10 round magazine, and two of the extended grip 14 round magazines. Also the original hard box, and the cardboard cover, instructions and factory paperwork, and the brush and cleaning tool. (also in the picture are a lock and sight for a rifle that are not supposed to go with this handgun)

from the manufacturers website:
 The CZ 2075 RAMI is a sub-compact semi-automatic based on the proven CZ 75 line of pistols. Just like the 75, the RAMI is double action/single action, allowing it to be carried in different conditions depending on the shooter’s preferences. Several safety devices are used including a firing pin block and a manual safety.

Incorporating the CZ double-stack magazine design, the little RAMI ships with a 10 round flush-mount magazine and 14 round extended magazine in the 9mm Luger version. With a 3” barrel and an unloaded weight of less than 26 ounces, the black polycoat, alloy-framed RAMI is ideal for concealed carry.

from Haus of Guns:
Down to a man every last person who had their hands on the CZ RAMI 2075 boasted about how accurate it was even at marginally long distances. I started at the typical self-defense distance of 7 yards (20 feet). Ironically as I backed up it became evident that this gun was factory sited to be dead on more in the 15 – 20 yard range. Not sure what type of self defense altercations are expected in the Czech Republic, but around here that’s quite a poke! In my hour of shooting I ran over 200 rounds of ammo through the little CZ without so much as a hiccup. ZERO malfunctions or disappointments and that makes Ebbs a happy shooter! I even went the extra mile to mix up ammo types and load it randomly even TRYING to get it to burp and she refused. The accuracy of the CZ is also afforded heavily by the precision of its sights. The rear sights are full adjustable for elevation and windage and they appear to have a green tint (not night sights) and a little glow to them in low light. It’s going to sound ridiculous to say this, but this gun almost felt more accurate at longer distances than it did at closer ranges. 
http://www.hausofguns.com/2011/04/02/cz-rami-2075-9mm-review/

Must have an AZ driver's license and sign bill of sale

title: For Sale:  Be careful selling.  Cops posing as military members
location: North Carolina, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Just a heads up guys.  When selling pistols be sure you are abiding by federal and North Carolina laws.  There are cops, feds, or anti-gun people posing as military members trying to buy guns without a permit.  They claim to be Army at Ft Bragg or Marines in Jacksonville.  They try to milk the fact that service members have a hard time getting PPPs.  They tug your heartstrings to get you to sell to them anyway so to pose gun owners as law breakers or charge you.  Whatever you do, always make sure your buyer has a NC Concealed Handgun Permit or Pistol Purchase Permit.  Also, be sure to get a bill of sale.  It will cover your butt if police come asking about a gun you sold that was used in a crime.  It isn't legally required, but it's a very good idea. http://bluelinedefense.com/d-files/bill_of_sale_1.pdf 

Our military members have honor, they will not break the law or go against their command to buy a gun.  If someone is trying to skirt the permit, do not sell to them.  It is likely a fed or an anti-gun person trying to get you in trouble.
